#import "../common.typ": *
== Data Processing

=== Triggering

- First step to identify the pulses for all the following Data processing steps.
- Event types are signal, noise, pulser, and each event is a 10s window.
- event rates for physics (background only, without calibration strings) is \~1 mHz, while with calibration, about 30-40 mHz (10-20 to 40-50 mHz, inner vs outer)
- Derivative trigger: a  fast algorithm to monitor and trigger online provides a basis to create event data and estimate detector response.
- Used for online trigerring in Apollo
- Averaged over few samples (where we set the number of samples?), set debounce time, dead time,
 - For low energy events, noise triggest uses (*is this sentence correct?*) offline DT and set optimal DT thresholds etc.(*?*)
- The optimal trigger: that try to give more accurate pulse description can be constructed with AP/ANPS taken prior, which is constructed using pulses marked by the DT.
  - OT algorithm -> Optimal Filter, low pass filter, down sampling, 4x more noise resolution for trigger


=== Pulse Amplitude
- Pulse amplitude acts the measure used to derive the final energy calculation
- $A(E,T) ~ a(E) dot G(T)$ = energy dependent + temperature dependent extract E.
- Pulse quality cuts construct OF
- Pulse basic parameters: baseline, baseline slope, baselineRMS, singleTrigger, NPulses
- baseline params (0 - 2.25s) (max baseline, etc)
- OF : $V^"OF"(omega) prop S(omega) / |N(omega)|^2 e^(-i omega t_"max"$
  -  pulse weight eval (3pt, 5pt? )


=== STABILIZATION
- TGS -> correct for temperature drifts -> baseline temperature calibration
  - Heater TGS, Calib TGS
- step params can change within runs & account for breaks/large jumps in operat. conditions
- Heater TGS: pulser events with const injected energy $A_(h(t)) = a_h(E) dot (P_1 + p_2 dot T...)$
- Calib TGS: reference peaks (2615 keV), DS dependent (not var) $V_"off"$ (from WP) $[G_"ele" - V_"out"]$
- can account for nonlinearities in gain temp dependence

=== ENERGY CALIBRATION
- Reconstruct the energy associated with each pulse after the corrections and filtering/cleaning using calibration.
- Use known $gamma$'s to calibrate the spectra obtained from previous steps.
  - calibration runs - #th232 +#co60
- using DCS calib initially & external calib after
- select stabilization method by looking at 2615 peak reconstruction
- create stabAmplitude histogram, identify peaks (2-4 peaks w/ best characteristic)
- highest amplitude peak w/ best sign SNR or reference peak
- two models per peak: Gauss & Crystal Ball -> BG spec (from calib runs)  compare & pick best fit. , Pol1+compton edge from gaus }
- correct pos's using Pol2 (zero intercept) calib peaks + 2615
- manual redoing for some calorimeters if: {conditions}

=== ENERGY ESTIMATOR
- Two estimators from two stab methods (should add decorrelation?)
- pick using FOM ratio: $W = alpha (C_h^2 / sigma_h^2) / (C_c^2 / sigma_c^2)$
-  Eval Fisher test statistic $F(W)$ for $(c-h)$; otherwise header
- $W < 1$ and $N > F(alpha)$ calib, otherwise heater
- When $alpha = 0.2$ gives \~ 100 channels for calibration stab Energy.

- *Energy thresholds:* determine trigger thresholds & efficiency curves
  - back compute injected pulse energy -> stab amplitude -> raw pulse Ampl using calib
    - add random noise waveform -> generate a simulated pulse
  - vary the injected pulse energy & estimate trigger efficiencies
    - ratio of OT triggered / Injected pulse
    - event is considered OT triggered if within width @ half max of peak
    - plot + fit efficiency-OT vs pulse energy using erf
    - invert & find threshold \@ efficiency $90\%$

- *Recover saturated pulses:* use the saturated pulses saturated width to estimate the energy -> good for high energy pulse analysis \~ cosmic muons / muon spectrum
  - saturated $|V_"out"| > 9.2 V tilde 15 "MeV"} =$ neutron captures / tri nucleon decay
  - "time above threshold" metric
  - take unsaturated pulses, calc $t_"above"$ a certain $V_"thres" -> (t_"above" = t_"sat")$
  - $E_"sat" = (V_"sat" - "Baseline"_"sat") / (V_"thresh" - "Baseline")$ \@ $(t_"above" = t_"sat")$: h/E
